---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MascotTip from '../../components/MascotTip.astro';
import AuthorByline from '../../components/AuthorByline.astro';
import EmailCapture from '../../components/EmailCapture.astro';
import FAQSection from '../../components/FAQSection.astro';
import QuickCompare from '../../components/QuickCompare.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Best Credit Card for Rent 2026"
  description="BILT is the only card earning points on rent with no fees. Tyler earns 30K points/year — full comparison of rent payment options."
>
  <article style="max-width: 48rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 8rem 0 4rem;">
    <h1 style="font-size: 3rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text); line-height: 1.1;">
        Best Credit Card for Rent 2026
    </h1>

    <AuthorByline date="March 15, 2026" />

    <div style="font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 1.8; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
      
      <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text); margin: 2rem 0;">
        <strong>Bottom line:</strong> BILT Mastercard is the only card that earns meaningful rewards on rent with zero fees. I earn 30,000 points per year ($300-600 value) on my $2,500/month rent.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you pay rent, this is the simplest optimization decision you can make. One card, zero fees, automatic points every month.
      </p>

      <QuickCompare
        cardIds={['bilt-mastercard', 'bilt-palladium', 'citi-double-cash']}
        category="rent"
        highlight="bilt-mastercard"
      />

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Why BILT Dominates This Category
      </h2>

      <p>
        Most credit cards either:
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Don't allow rent payments at all</li>
        <li>Process rent as a cash advance (high fees, no rewards)</li>
        <li>Work through third-party services that charge 2.5-3% fees</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        BILT is designed specifically for rent. They mail a check to your landlord for free. You earn 1 point per dollar. No transaction fees, no cash advance nonsense.
      </p>

      <p>
        The catch: You need 5 transactions per month on the card for rent to earn points. But this is trivially easy to hit (see my setup below).
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h3 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
          BILT Mastercard (2.0)
        </h3>

        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          <div>
            <div style="font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">RENT REWARDS</div>
            <div style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-success);">1x points/dollar</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div style="font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">ANNUAL FEE</div>
            <div style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text);">$0</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div style="font-size: 0.875rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">TRANSACTION FEE</div>
            <div style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text);">$0</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Other Rewards:</p>
        <ul style="margin: 0 0 1.5rem 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8;">
          <li>3x points on dining</li>
          <li>2x points on travel</li>
          <li>1x points on everything else</li>
        </ul>

        <p style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Point Value:</p>
        <ul style="margin: 0 0 1.5rem 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8;">
          <li>Transfer to 100+ airline/hotel partners</li>
          <li>Use toward rent credits or fitness classes</li>
          <li>Redeem for travel or statement credits</li>
          <li>Use toward home down payment (25K points = $250)</li>
        </ul>

        <a href="https://www.bfrg.com/p/credit-cards/bilt-credit-card/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="display: inline-block; padding: 0.875rem 1.75rem; background-color: var(--color-accent); color: white; border-radius: var(--radius-sm); font-weight: 600; text-decoration: none; transition: background 0.2s;" onmouseover="this.style.backgroundColor='#e67e22'" onmouseout="this.style.backgroundColor='var(--color-accent)'">
          Apply for BILT Mastercard →
        </a>
        <!-- TODO: Add affiliate tracking -->
      </div>

      <MascotTip type="pick">
        <p>This is my rent card. $2,500/month = 30,000 points/year. I transfer them to Alaska Airlines for West Coast flights. Zero fees, zero hassle, and I was paying rent anyway.</p>
      </MascotTip>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        The Math: What You'll Actually Earn
      </h2>

      <p>
        Let's break down the real value at different rent levels:
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); overflow-x: auto; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9375rem;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border);">
              <th style="text-align: left; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Monthly Rent</th>
              <th style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Annual Points</th>
              <th style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Conservative Value</th>
              <th style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">Optimized Value</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">$1,500</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">18,000</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success);">$180-234</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">$360+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">$2,000</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">24,000</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success);">$240-312</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">$480+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); background-color: #f0fdf4;">
              <td style="padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">$2,500</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 700;">30,000</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success);">$300-390</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 900;">$600+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border-light);">
              <td style="padding: 1rem;">$3,000</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; font-weight: 600;">36,000</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success);">$360-468</td>
              <td style="text-align: right; padding: 1rem; color: var(--color-success); font-weight: 700;">$720+</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        <strong>Conservative value:</strong> 1-1.3 cents per point (statement credit, rent discounts)  
        <strong>Optimized value:</strong> 2+ cents per point (airline transfers, hotel partners)
      </p>

      <p>
        Even at the conservative end, you're getting $300-400/year in value on typical rent. That's free money for doing exactly what you were already doing.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Alternative: BILT Palladium
      </h2>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h3 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">
          BILT Palladium (Invite-Only)
        </h3>

        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          Same rent rewards (1x points), but with premium perks:
        </p>

        <ul style="margin: 0 0 1.5rem 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8;">
          <li>2x points on groceries (vs 1x on BILT 2.0)</li>
          <li>3x points on dining (same as 2.0)</li>
          <li>Cell phone protection</li>
          <li>Trip delay protection</li>
          <li>Still $0 annual fee</li>
        </ul>

        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 0;">
          If you get invited (usually after 6-12 months with BILT 2.0), it's a straight upgrade. Same rent rewards, better everyday rewards.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        What About Other Cards?
      </h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Can I use a regular cashback card for rent?</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        Only through third-party services like Plastiq, which charge 2.5-2.85% fees.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let's do the math on $2,500 rent with a 2% cashback card:
      </p>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 1.5rem 2rem; line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Plastiq fee (2.85%): $71.25/month = $855/year</li>
        <li>Card rewards (2%): $50/month = $600/year</li>
        <li><strong>Net result:</strong> -$255/year (you lose money)</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Even premium cards with 3-4% categories lose money after fees. BILT is the only card with zero rent fees.
      </p>

      <MascotTip type="warning">
        <p>Avoid services that claim you can "pay rent with any card for free." If it sounds too good to be true, check the fine print. Most charge hidden fees, process as cash advances, or require minimum spending that defeats the purpose.</p>
      </MascotTip>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        How to Hit the 5-Transaction Minimum
      </h2>

      <p>
        BILT requires 5 transactions per month for rent to earn points. Here's my system:
      </p>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Set-It-and-Forget-It Approach</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">Put 5 recurring subscriptions on autopay:</p>
        <ul style="margin: 0 0 1rem 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8;">
          <li>Netflix ($15.49/month)</li>
          <li>Spotify ($10.99/month)</li>
          <li>iCloud storage ($2.99/month)</li>
          <li>Amazon Prime ($14.99/month)</li>
          <li>ChatGPT Plus ($20/month)</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 0;">
          <strong>Total:</strong> 5 transactions, automatically. Never think about it again.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0;">
        <h4 style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text);">Active Use Approach</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">If you use BILT as an everyday card anyway:</p>
        <ul style="margin: 0 0 1rem 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8;">
          <li>Morning coffee: 1 transaction</li>
          <li>Groceries: 1 transaction</li>
          <li>Gas: 1 transaction</li>
          <li>Dinner out: 1 transaction</li>
          <li>Any online purchase: 1 transaction</li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 0;">
          You'll hit 5 transactions in the first week of the month naturally.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>

      <FAQSection faqs={[
        {
          question: "Does my landlord need to accept credit cards?",
          answer: "No. BILT mails them a physical check. From your landlord's perspective, it's just a check in the mail — they don't know or care that you paid with a credit card. This works with any landlord, including big property management companies and individual landlords who only accept checks."
        },
        {
          question: "Will paying rent with BILT count as a cash advance?",
          answer: "No. BILT processes rent as a regular purchase, not a cash advance. You won't pay cash advance fees, and you won't accrue interest at a higher rate. As long as you pay your statement balance in full each month (which you should), there's no interest at all."
        },
        {
          question: "What happens if I forget to make 5 transactions in a month?",
          answer: "You won't earn points on your rent for that month. Everything else (dining, travel, etc.) still earns points, but the rent payment specifically won't count. Your other purchases still earn normally. The 5-transaction rule only affects rent rewards."
        },
        {
          question: "Can I pay a mortgage with BILT?",
          answer: "Unfortunately no. BILT only works for rent payments to landlords, not mortgage payments to banks. If you own your home, this card won't help with your housing payment — focus on optimizing other spending categories instead."
        },
        {
          question: "What if my rent is more than my credit limit?",
          answer: "You can request a credit limit increase through the BILT app. Most people with good credit get approved for $5,000-15,000 limits initially, which covers typical rent. If your rent exceeds your limit, you can also make partial payments (though this adds complexity). Most users don't have this issue after the first limit increase."
        }
      ]} />

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        The Bottom Line
      </h2>

      <p>
        If you pay rent, get the BILT Mastercard. It's the only free way to earn rewards on rent.
      </p>

      <p>
        Start with BILT 2.0. If you get invited to Palladium later, upgrade. Either way, you're earning 30,000+ points per year on money you were spending anyway.
      </p>

      <p>
        For most renters, this single card adds $300-600/year in value. No fees. No complexity. Just automatic rewards every month.
      </p>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 800; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem; color: var(--color-text);">
        Related Articles
      </h2>

      <ul style="margin: 1.5rem 0 2rem 0; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/how-to-pay-rent-with-credit-card" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">How to Pay Rent with a Credit Card (Full Setup Guide)</a>
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/credit-card-stacking" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">Credit Card Stacking Guide</a>
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">
          <a href="/strategies/secret-sauce" style="color: var(--color-secondary); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 600;">How I Earn $3,500+/Year in Rewards</a>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <EmailCapture
        variant="article-end"
        headline="Want the full card stack strategy?"
        description="Get Tyler's complete system for optimizing every spending category, not just rent."
        buttonText="Get free access"
      />

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
